{"ts": "2026-04-12T15:05:57.082954+00:00", "event": "stream", "session_id": "chat_1776006354868_kv3ek", "query": "what is written inside this", "corrected_query": null, "model": "llama-3.3-70b-versatile", "role_mode": "assistant", "prompt_template": "default", "route": "multimodal", "route_reason": "Current request contains uploaded multimodal content.", "route_confidence": 1.0, "route_source": "llm", "fallback": false, "used_rag": true, "cache_hit": false, "corrected": false, "citations": 1, "retrieved_documents": ["Assignment 3.pdf"], "retrieval": {"matches": 1, "hybrid_search": true, "context_chars": 628, "top_score": 1.0}, "response": "The provided context appears to be related to a data analysis assignment, specifically focusing on hypothesis testing. Hypothesis testing is a crucial concept in data analysis that involves making informed decisions based on data. It is used to determine whether a hypothesis is true or not, by analyzing the data and drawing conclusions.\n\nHypothesis testing typically involves several main steps. These include formulating a hypothesis, collecting data, analyzing the data, and making a decision based on the analysis. The hypothesis is usually formulated as a null hypothesis (H\u2080) and an alternative hypothesis (H\u2081). The null hypothesis represents a statement of no effect or no difference, while the alternative hypothesis represents a statement of an effect or difference.\n\nThe null hypothesis (H\u2080) and alternative hypothesis (H\u2081) are two fundamental concepts in hypothesis testing. For example, consider a scenario where a company wants to determine whether a new marketing strategy is effective. The null hypothesis could be \"the new marketing strategy has no effect on sales,\" while the alternative hypothesis could be \"the new marketing strategy increases sales.\" Other examples of H\u2080 and H\u2081 include: \n- H\u2080: A new diet has no effect on weight loss, H\u2081: A new diet leads to weight loss\n- H\u2080: A new exercise routine has no effect on overall health, H\u2081: A new exercise routine improves overall health\n- H\u2080: A new teaching method has no effect on student performance, H\u2081: A new teaching method improves student performance\n\nIn hypothesis testing, there are two types of errors that can occur: Type I error and Type II error. A Type I error occurs when a true null hypothesis is rejected, while a Type II error occurs when a false null hypothesis is not rejected. For instance, a Type I error would occur if a company concludes that a new marketing strategy is effective when it is not. On the other hand, a Type II error would occur if a company concludes that a new marketing strategy is not effective when it actually is.\n\nThe level of significance (\u03b1) is another important concept in hypothesis testing. It represents the maximum probability of making a Type I error. The 5% level of significance is commonly used, which means that there is a 5% chance of rejecting a true null hypothesis. This level of significance is widely accepted as a standard in many fields, including business, medicine, and social sciences.", "latency_ms": 2203.89}
