{"ts": "2026-04-25T09:15:03.522827+00:00", "event": "stream", "user_id": "43489bbd9cf64a9c923017db8a244011", "session_id": "chat_1777108495769_0wfq7", "query": "Kaise ho.", "corrected_query": "Kaise ho.", "model": "llama-3.3-70b-versatile", "role_mode": "assistant", "prompt_template": "generate_prompt", "route": "direct", "route_reason": "Short general query without retrieval signals.", "route_confidence": 0.72, "route_source": "heuristic", "fallback": false, "used_rag": false, "cache_hit": false, "corrected": true, "citations": 0, "retrieved_documents": [], "retrieval": {"matches": 0, "hybrid_search": true, "context_chars": 0, "top_score": 0.0}, "response": "# \ud83d\udd25 Introduction to Hindi Greetings \ud83d\ude4f\nI'm doing well, thank you for asking. \"Kaise ho\" is a Hindi greeting that translates to \"how are you\" in English.\n\n## \ud83d\udcda Explanation\n\"Kaise ho\" is a common way to ask about someone's well-being in Hindi. It's a polite and friendly greeting used to show interest in the other person's life.\n\n## \ud83d\udd39 Types / Components\n- **Formal greeting**: Used in formal situations or when speaking to someone older or in a position of authority.\n- **Informal greeting**: Used with friends, family, or in casual conversations.\n\n## \u26a1 Examples\n- **Formal**: \"Kaise ho, aap?\" (How are you, sir/ma'am?)\n- **Informal**: \"Kaise ho, yaar?\" (How are you, friend?)\n\n## \ud83c\udfaf Summary\n- \"Kaise ho\" is a Hindi greeting that means \"how are you\" in English.\n- It's used to show interest in someone's well-being and can be formal or informal depending on the context.\n- Responding with \"main theek hoon\" (I'm fine) or \"main accha hoon\" (I'm good) is a common way to reply to this greeting.", "latency_ms": 1953.83}
{"ts": "2026-04-25T09:29:25.228389+00:00", "event": "stream", "user_id": "43489bbd9cf64a9c923017db8a244011", "session_id": "chat_1777108495769_0wfq7", "query": "Kaise ho.", "corrected_query": "Kaise ho.", "model": "llama-3.3-70b-versatile", "role_mode": "assistant", "prompt_template": "generate_prompt", "route": "direct", "route_reason": "Short general query without retrieval signals.", "route_confidence": 0.72, "route_source": "heuristic", "fallback": false, "used_rag": false, "cache_hit": false, "corrected": true, "citations": 0, "retrieved_documents": [], "retrieval": {"matches": 0, "hybrid_search": true, "context_chars": 0, "top_score": 0.0}, "response": "# \ud83d\udd25 Introduction to Hindi Greetings \ud83d\ude4f\nKaise ho is a Hindi greeting that translates to \"How are you?\" in English. It's a common way to start a conversation in Hindi.\n\n## \ud83d\udcda Explanation\nKaise ho is a phrase used to inquire about someone's well-being or state of mind. It's a polite and friendly greeting that shows interest in the other person's life.\n\n## \ud83d\udd39 Types / Components\n- **Formal greeting**: Kaise ho is a formal greeting, often used in professional or formal settings.\n- **Informal greeting**: In informal settings, people may use shorter versions like \"Kaise\" or \"Kaisa ho\".\n\n## \u26a1 Examples\n- **Formal example**: When meeting a teacher or elder, you can say \"Namaste, kaise ho?\" (Hello, how are you?).\n- **Informal example**: With friends, you can say \"Kaise ho, yaar?\" (How are you, friend?).\n\n## \ud83c\udfaf Summary\n- Kaise ho is a Hindi greeting that means \"How are you?\".\n- It's used in both formal and informal settings.\n- The phrase shows interest in the other person's well-being and is a polite way to start a conversation.", "latency_ms": 1981.21}
{"ts": "2026-04-25T09:33:57.915252+00:00", "event": "stream", "user_id": "43489bbd9cf64a9c923017db8a244011", "session_id": "chat_1777109635441_nlq7q", "query": "Kaise ho.", "corrected_query": null, "model": "llama-3.3-70b-versatile", "role_mode": "assistant", "prompt_template": "generate_prompt", "route": "direct", "route_reason": "Short general query without retrieval signals.", "route_confidence": 0.72, "route_source": "heuristic", "fallback": false, "used_rag": false, "cache_hit": false, "corrected": false, "citations": 0, "retrieved_documents": [], "retrieval": {"matches": 0, "hybrid_search": true, "context_chars": 0, "top_score": 0.0}, "response": "# \ud83d\udd25 Introduction to Hindi Greetings \ud83d\ude4f\nKaise ho is a Hindi greeting that translates to \"How are you?\" in English. It's a common way to start a conversation in Hindi.\n\n## \ud83d\udcda Explanation\nKaise ho is a casual greeting used to inquire about someone's well-being. It's often used among friends, family, or acquaintances. In formal situations, you might use a more formal greeting like \"Namaste\" or \"Namaskar\".\n\n## \ud83d\udd39 Types / Components\n- **Kaise**: This means \"how\" in Hindi.\n- **Ho**: This is a verb that means \"are\" in Hindi.\n\n## \u26a1 Examples\n- **Person A**: Kaise ho? (How are you?)\n- **Person B**: Main theek hoon, dhanyavad. (I'm fine, thank you.)\n\n## \ud83c\udfaf Summary\n- Kaise ho is a casual Hindi greeting that means \"How are you?\"\n- It's used to start a conversation and inquire about someone's well-being.\n- You can respond with \"Main theek hoon\" (I'm fine) or a similar phrase to indicate your well-being.", "latency_ms": 2452.63}
